@glenn-jocher, is it possible to easily modify the code to test on arbitrary image sizes (not rounded to multiples of 64)? 
What is the rationale behind using [64](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov3/blob/master/train.py#L67) as grid size and normalizing widths and heights? I think it was previously set to 32. Will the mosaic dataloader break if all the images don't have the same size? For example if I use the standard yolov3-spp-608 cfg, the model won't actually use 608 for training or testing. Isn't that misleading? 
While testing you use letterbox to pad the images to nearest 64 multiple. Is it easy (simple modifications to python code) and does it make sense to turn off padding in 1. training (mosaic) 2. testing (letterbox)?

@anisaha1 your dataset image sizes are completely unrelated to the --img-size specified in train, test, or detect.py. They can be any shape and size. You can observe the result in train*.jpg and test*.jpg once you start training.

64 is used as a prelude to adding a P6 level to yolo which will use stride 64.

Also, none of the cfg settings are used during training, only the architecture. The training settings come from the argparser and the hyps dictionary in train.py.
